  <h1>Rideshare Insurance Phases Explained</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Period 0: App off</h2><p>Driver is not logged into the rideshare app. The driver&rsquo;s personal auto insurance is solely responsible. Rideshare companies provide no coverage. Claims are made against the driver&rsquo;s personal insurer, subject to the driver&rsquo;s policy limits.</p>
  <h2>Period 1: Logged in, waiting</h2><p>Driver is logged into the app but has not accepted a ride. Uber and Lyft each provide: $50,000 bodily injury per person, $100,000 bodily injury per accident, $25,000 property damage — but only contingently (if the driver&rsquo;s personal insurance denies coverage, typically because it excludes commercial use).</p>
  <h2>Periods 2 and 3: En route or carrying passenger</h2><p>Period 2: Driver accepted a ride request and is on the way to pick up the passenger. Period 3: Passenger is in the vehicle. Both Uber and Lyft provide $1,000,000 in third-party liability coverage per accident. Both also provide contingent comprehensive and collision coverage for vehicle damage (subject to a $1,000–$2,500 deductible and only if the driver carries personal comp/collision).</p>
  <h2>State variations</h2><p>Some states mandate additional rideshare coverage. California, New York, and Illinois have enacted specific rideshare insurance laws that may provide additional protections. Period 1 limits have been increased in some states.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-rideshare-accident-claims-work">how rideshare claims work</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
